references: The metric calculated using eq. 7 allows us to be more sensitive for parameter differences and specific error types: incorrect spin group assignment (significant number of missed/fake resonances). Fig. 4 exemplifies the underlying principle: where the true ladder has 7 resonances of two spin groups (Jπsuperscript𝐽𝜋J^{\pi} = 3.0+superscript3.03.0^{+} and Jπsuperscript𝐽𝜋J^{\pi} = 4.0+superscript4.04.0^{+}) in a given energy region, while the estimated ladder has 14 resonances. A straightforward calculation of strength functions for both ladders gives approximately equal values Struel≈Sfitlsubscriptsuperscript𝑆𝑙truesubscriptsuperscript𝑆𝑙fitS^{l}_{\text{true}}\approx S^{l}_{\text{fit}} (calculation results for presented example are given in table 1).

Notably, all of the true resonances were correctly identified for a given case, but the spin group assignment for part of the resonances was incorrect. Specifically, for a resonance at 214.75 eV, the spin group was initially assigned incorrectly - see Fig. 4 a). For this resonance, the spin group was flipped, and the model was then refitted to the same data with the spin group reassigned - Fig. 4 b). The error metrics before and after the spin group reassignment (SGR) are presented in Table 1. This adjustment highlights the impact of correct spin group assignments on the metrics εSFsubscript𝜀SF\varepsilon_{\text{SF}} and εPSFsubscript𝜀PSF\varepsilon_{\text{PSF}}, underscoring their different sensitivity to errors in spin group classification.

references: Multiple datasets were generated for training, hypotheses testing, and validation. Their characteristics are presented in Table 2. The purpose and differences of these datasets are described below.

The performance of ARIS is compared for 2 groups of test scenarios: when data includes resonances of single or multiple spin groups, exploring the impact of correct spin group assignment. Thus the first study group estimates the performance of ARIS when the data contains resonances from a single spin group, thereby eliminating uncertainty related to correct spin group assignment. The simplest way to simulate this scenario is to generate observables that include resonances only of the first spin group, Jπ=3.0+superscript𝐽𝜋superscript3.0J^{\pi}=3.0^{+} (datasets with NSG=1subscript𝑁SG1N_{\text{SG}}=1 in table 2). The datasets of the first group (A, B) were generated with resonances from only one spin group Jπ=3.0+superscript𝐽𝜋superscript3.0J^{\pi}=3.0^{+}, while datasets (C, D) contain data for both spin groups. Average parameters for resonances are shown in Table 3.

Dataset A is used for the initial estimation of hyperparameter value (denoted as TR - training in Table 2). For this test, ARIS is supplied with correct DCMs (full covariance matrices without any distortions), and correct values of average parameters are used during the fitting process.
Dataset B serves as a validation dataset (marked V in the Purpose column of Table 2) - to check if the performance on unseen data is consistent with the results obtained from Dataset A.
